<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="376" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1117,1936]" pageId="1" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1730,1756]" pageId="1" pageNumber="376">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species can be distinguished from other species of the genus by the wide and flat aedeagal shaft with a subapical pair of long and bifurcate processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="376" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1117,1936]" pageId="1" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1802,1828]" pageId="1" pageNumber="376">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species name is derived from the words “ 
<emphasis box="[912,979,1802,1828]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="376">furca-</emphasis>
” and “ 
<emphasis box="[1060,1169,1803,1828]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="376">processus</emphasis>
”, referring to the bifurcate aedeagal processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
